WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:04.181
Professor Ben Polak:
So last time we covered a

00:00:04.181 --> 00:00:06.987
whole bunch of new ideas,
and it was really quite a lot

00:00:06.987 --> 00:00:10.422
of ideas for one class.
Here's some of the ideas we

00:00:10.422 --> 00:00:12.836
covered.
We talked about information

00:00:12.836 --> 00:00:16.375
sets, and these were ways to
allow us to model imperfect

00:00:16.375 --> 00:00:19.300
information.
So what's imperfect information?

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:23.324
It's a way of being able to
capture both simultaneity in

00:00:23.324 --> 00:00:26.690
moves and sequential moves in
the same game.

00:00:26.690 --> 00:00:30.339
So it's a way that's going to
allow us to meld the lessons

00:00:30.339 --> 00:00:33.540
from before the mid-term and
after the mid-term.

00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:36.616
Then we talked about what
strategies meant in this

00:00:36.616 --> 00:00:39.378
context, and the basic idea is
strategies are

00:00:39.378 --> 00:00:42.705
instructions--strategies for
each player--give them an

00:00:42.705 --> 00:00:45.970
instruction at each of their
information sets.

00:00:45.970 --> 00:00:48.145
Then we talked about what
sub-games were,

00:00:48.145 --> 00:00:49.940
and, leaving aside
technicalities,

00:00:49.940 --> 00:00:52.280
sub-games were just games
within games.

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:56.095
And finally we introduced the
idea of sub-game perfection

00:00:56.095 --> 00:00:59.979
which is our new solution
concept that refines the idea of

00:00:59.979 --> 00:01:02.803
Nash equilibrium.
What sub-game perfection is

00:01:02.803 --> 00:01:05.798
going to do is it's going to
instruct the players to play a

00:01:05.798 --> 00:01:07.760
Nash equilibrium in every
sub-game.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:11.571
Another way of saying it is,
a sub-game equilibrium is a

00:01:11.571 --> 00:01:15.590
Nash equilibrium in the whole
game, but in each sub-game it

00:01:15.590 --> 00:01:19.781
induces Nash play as well.
Now, we're going to see today

00:01:19.781 --> 00:01:22.236
examples.
If we have time I'll go through

00:01:22.236 --> 00:01:25.354
three different examples,
and I'll tell you at the end of

00:01:25.354 --> 00:01:28.529
each example what it is I'm
hoping to be able to take away

00:01:28.529 --> 00:01:31.590
from that example.
So, last time was a lot of

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:34.000
formal stuff.
Today is going to be a lot of

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.130
examples.
Okay, that's our agenda.

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:42.080
Here's a game.
Here's our first example.

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.445
And I call this example,
I call this game,

00:01:44.445 --> 00:01:47.560
"don't screw up," for reasons
we'll see in a minute.

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:52.319
So this is a game in which
Player 1 has to choose between

00:01:52.319 --> 00:01:56.095
Up and Down.
If Player 1 chooses Up then

00:01:56.095 --> 00:02:01.650
Player 2 gets to move and
chooses between left and right.

00:02:01.650 --> 00:02:06.661
And if Player 2 chooses left
then Player 1 gets to move again

00:02:06.661 --> 00:02:10.170
and Player 1 chooses between up
or down.

00:02:10.170 --> 00:02:14.000
Everyone looking at that game?
So why don't we play this game

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.009
since we haven't played a game
for a while.

00:02:16.009 --> 00:02:17.780
We'll play a couple of games
today.

00:02:17.780 --> 00:02:21.960
So what I'm going to do is
let's divide the class in two.

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:25.210
So if I just draw a line down
the middle of the class,

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:28.828
everybody to my left (to your
right), everybody on this side

00:02:28.828 --> 00:02:32.650
of the class is a Player 1.
Okay you're all Player 1's.

00:02:32.650 --> 00:02:35.942
And everyone on this side of
class you're Player 2,

00:02:35.942 --> 00:02:40.090
including you guys hiding from
the camera, you're Player 2's.

00:02:40.090 --> 00:02:43.479
Okay, so let's figure out what
we're going to do.

00:02:43.479 --> 00:02:46.509
Everyone had the time to look
at the game?

00:02:46.509 --> 00:02:51.465
So Player 1's you get to move
first, those of you who are

00:02:51.465 --> 00:02:55.270
going to choose Down raise your
hand now.

00:02:55.270 --> 00:02:58.099
Raise your hand.
Wave it in the air.

00:02:58.099 --> 00:03:00.080
Keep it up so the camera can
see you.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:05.160
And those of you who are going
to choose Up raise your hands.

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:07.294
Lots more Ups.
Those of you who chose Up why

00:03:07.294 --> 00:03:09.639
don't you all stand up.
I don't want to do all the

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:11.332
exercise here,
so all those who chose Up,

00:03:11.332 --> 00:03:11.840
stand up.

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:17.445
So you can see that choosing
down ends the game,

00:03:17.445 --> 00:03:20.099
so this many people are still
playing the game.

00:03:20.099 --> 00:03:23.463
Everyone who is still sitting
down, everyone who sat down here

00:03:23.463 --> 00:03:25.975
has exited.
All right, Player 2's you get

00:03:25.975 --> 00:03:27.720
to move now.
So Player 2's,

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:31.615
those of you who choose right,
including the people on this

00:03:31.615 --> 00:03:34.592
aisle,
those people who choose right

00:03:34.592 --> 00:03:38.110
raise your hand now--one right
over there.

00:03:38.110 --> 00:03:41.660
Those of you who choose left
raise your hands.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:45.747
Why don't you guys all stand
up, just to get you awake on a

00:03:45.747 --> 00:03:48.990
Monday morning,
everyone's sleepy otherwise.

00:03:48.990 --> 00:03:54.319
Let's go back to Player
2's--sorry Player 1--those of

00:03:54.319 --> 00:04:00.090
you who are still in the game.
So those of you who chose Up

00:04:00.090 --> 00:04:03.738
the first time,
how many of you now choose

00:04:03.738 --> 00:04:05.833
down?
Raise your hand if you choose

00:04:05.833 --> 00:04:08.579
down;
and raise your hand if you

00:04:08.579 --> 00:04:10.936
choose up.
Just to get a sample of this,

00:04:10.936 --> 00:04:13.660
let's get the 2's to sit down
again so people can see them.

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.677
So 2's sit down.
Those of you Player 1's who are

00:04:17.677 --> 00:04:22.220
still in the game who were
choosing up raise your hand now.

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:23.720
I think that's everybody,
is that correct?

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.847
Okay, you can all sit down.
So let's just talk about this

00:04:26.847 --> 00:04:28.740
game for a while and then we'll
analyze it.

00:04:28.740 --> 00:04:31.778
Now, this is not a difficult
game from the point of view of

00:04:31.778 --> 00:04:33.769
stuff we've done since the
mid-term.

00:04:33.769 --> 00:04:36.833
It's pretty clear what we
should do in this game by

00:04:36.833 --> 00:04:39.810
backward induction.
So why don't we start there.

00:04:39.810 --> 00:04:44.491
Okay, so by backward induction,
we find that if Player 1 gets

00:04:44.491 --> 00:04:48.861
to move a second time then
they're choosing between 4 and

00:04:48.861 --> 00:04:51.819
3,
and they're going to choose 4.

00:04:51.819 --> 00:04:57.041
Player 2, if they get to move,
knowing that Player 1 is going

00:04:57.041 --> 00:05:01.320
to choose up tomorrow,
they're going to be choosing

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:05.779
between 3 if they choose left or
2 if they choose right.

00:05:05.779 --> 00:05:07.234
So they're going to stay in the
game and choose left,

00:05:07.234 --> 00:05:08.130
which is what most of you did.

00:05:11.279 --> 00:05:14.271
Finally, Player 1 at the
beginning of the game,

00:05:14.271 --> 00:05:18.044
knows that Player 2 is going to
choose left whereupon she's

00:05:18.044 --> 00:05:21.197
going to choose up,
so if she chooses Up she's

00:05:21.197 --> 00:05:24.702
going to end up getting 4,
and if she chooses Down she's

00:05:24.702 --> 00:05:27.490
going to get 2,
so she's going to choose Up.

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:30.024
So it's clear what backward
induction does in this game and

00:05:30.024 --> 00:05:31.860
that's what most people did in
the game.

00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:37.050
Is that right?
However, not everybody did it.

00:05:37.050 --> 00:05:40.410
Some of the Player 1's
actually, why don't you raise

00:05:40.410 --> 00:05:44.166
your hand, those people who
chose Down--the ones who chose

00:05:44.166 --> 00:05:45.664
down.
There were more than that.

00:05:45.664 --> 00:05:47.899
You can all stand up.
Those of you who didn't stand

00:05:47.899 --> 00:05:50.085
up just now raise your hands.
People are hiding now,

00:05:50.085 --> 00:05:52.182
but that's okay.
Those people who chose Down,

00:05:52.182 --> 00:05:54.668
they may have had a reason for
choosing Down,

00:05:54.668 --> 00:05:58.002
and their reason for choosing
Down might have been that they

00:05:58.002 --> 00:06:01.336
thought--even though they can do
backward induction--so even

00:06:01.336 --> 00:06:04.444
though they know that by
backward induction Up gets them

00:06:04.444 --> 00:06:08.569
the better answer--they might be
worried that if they choose Up,

00:06:08.569 --> 00:06:11.879
Player 2 will screw up and
choose right.

00:06:11.879 --> 00:06:16.554
Notice that if Player 2 chooses
right then Player 1 only gets 1,

00:06:16.554 --> 00:06:20.231
whereas Down yielded 2.
So in some sense Down was the

00:06:20.231 --> 00:06:24.189
"safe" thing to do for Player 1
given that they might be worried

00:06:24.189 --> 00:06:27.467
that Player 2 might screw up.
Does that roughly--just nod if

00:06:27.467 --> 00:06:29.495
this is the case:
for those people who chose down

00:06:29.495 --> 00:06:31.269
is that kind of what you were
thinking?

00:06:31.269 --> 00:06:33.833
Some people are shaking their
heads, but some people are

00:06:33.833 --> 00:06:35.120
nodding.
That's a good sign.

00:06:35.120 --> 00:06:40.050
Now why might Player 2 in fact
screw up and choose right.

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:43.251
Because Player 2 might,
themselves, think that Player 1

00:06:43.251 --> 00:06:47.379
might screw up at this stage.
If Player 1 were to screw up at

00:06:47.379 --> 00:06:51.883
the last stage and choose down,
then Player 2 by choosing left

00:06:51.883 --> 00:06:55.654
would only get 1,
and for him the safe option

00:06:55.654 --> 00:06:58.629
therefore is right which yields
2.

00:06:58.629 --> 00:07:01.990
So, to get the backward
induction answer here--which

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:05.679
most of us did--to get the
backward induction answer here

00:07:05.679 --> 00:07:09.105
relies on Player 1 trusting
Player 2 to play backward

00:07:09.105 --> 00:07:12.029
induction,
and that requires Player 1 to

00:07:12.029 --> 00:07:16.027
have trust in Player 2 trusting
Player 1 not to screw up in the

00:07:16.027 --> 00:07:17.802
last stage.
So say it again,

00:07:17.802 --> 00:07:21.127
Player 1 needs Player 2 not to
screw up, and that means Player

00:07:21.127 --> 00:07:24.670
1 needs to trust that Player 2
will trust her not to screw up.

00:07:24.670 --> 00:07:28.999
Everyone see the game?
Okay, so let's try and analyze

00:07:28.999 --> 00:07:33.649
this game using what we learned
last time and see what we find.

00:07:33.649 --> 00:07:37.207
So the first thing to do is
let's look at strategies in this

00:07:37.207 --> 00:07:39.271
game.
So Player 2 just has two

00:07:39.271 --> 00:07:43.101
strategies, left and right,
because Player 2 only has one

00:07:43.101 --> 00:07:47.068
information set--and notice this
game is actually a game of

00:07:47.068 --> 00:07:50.829
perfect information so it's
going to be very easy.

00:07:50.829 --> 00:07:55.956
Player 1 has two information
sets, this information set and

00:07:55.956 --> 00:07:59.860
that information set.
At each of them Player 1 has

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:03.399
two choices so she must have
four strategies in all.

00:08:03.399 --> 00:08:10.410
So this game when we put it in
its matrix form is going to be a

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:13.029
4 x 2 game.
Here it is.

00:08:13.029 --> 00:08:16.727
And the strategies for Player 1
are (Up, up),

00:08:16.727 --> 00:08:19.499
(Up, down), (Down,
up), and (Down,

00:08:19.499 --> 00:08:23.860
down).
And the strategies for Player 2

00:08:23.860 --> 00:08:28.217
are just left and right.
And now we can put the payoffs

00:08:28.217 --> 00:08:29.861
in.
So ((Up, up),

00:08:29.861 --> 00:08:37.750
left) gets us (4,3).
((Up, up), right) gets us (1,2).

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:44.460
((Up, down),
left) gets us (3,1).

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:48.735
((Up, up, right) gets us (1,2)
again: we end up exiting the

00:08:48.735 --> 00:08:52.031
game here.
(Down, up) is easy because it's

00:08:52.031 --> 00:08:56.697
just exiting the game at the
first stage, so all of these are

00:08:56.697 --> 00:09:00.350
going to be just (2,1).
Everyone happy with that?

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:04.230
So what I've done is translated
the game into its matrix form.

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:10.009
And let's look for Nash
equilibria in this game.

00:09:10.009 --> 00:09:12.870
Let me do it at the board since
it's quite easy at this stage.

00:09:12.870 --> 00:09:15.802
So to look for Nash equilibria,
let's just worry about pure

00:09:15.802 --> 00:09:20.093
strategy equilibria for now.
So if Player 2 was choosing

00:09:20.093 --> 00:09:24.716
left then Player 1's best
response is the (Up,

00:09:24.716 --> 00:09:28.130
up) strategy.
And if Player 2 is choosing

00:09:28.130 --> 00:09:31.541
right, then Player 1's best
response is either (Down,

00:09:31.541 --> 00:09:33.049
up) or (Down,
down).

00:09:33.049 --> 00:09:34.330
That's exactly the conversation
we just had.

00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:37.975
If Player 2 was going to "screw
up" and choose right then Player

00:09:37.975 --> 00:09:40.580
1 wants to get out of the game
immediately.

00:09:40.580 --> 00:09:44.259
Conversely, if Player 1 is
choosing (Up,

00:09:44.259 --> 00:09:49.354
up) then Player 2 is happy and
is going to choose left,

00:09:49.354 --> 00:09:53.876
trusting Player 1.
If Player 1 was going to choose

00:09:53.876 --> 00:09:57.821
(Up, down), however,
that's Player 1 screwing up at

00:09:57.821 --> 00:10:01.170
the second stage.
So in that case Player 2 wants

00:10:01.170 --> 00:10:03.590
to get out of the game and
choose right.

00:10:03.590 --> 00:10:07.424
If Player 1 is choosing (Down,
up) then Player 2 is

00:10:07.424 --> 00:10:11.259
actually--it doesn't matter
they're indifferent.

00:10:11.259 --> 00:10:14.315
And if Player 2 is choosing
(Down, down) then once again

00:10:14.315 --> 00:10:17.759
Player 2 is indifferent since
they don't get to move at all.

00:10:17.759 --> 00:10:23.503
So from this we see that there
are three Nash equilibria,

00:10:23.503 --> 00:10:26.580
let me call them 1,2,
and 3.

00:10:26.580 --> 00:10:33.139
So one Nash equilibrium is
((Up, up), left).

00:10:33.139 --> 00:10:40.730
Another Nash equilibrium is
((Down, up, right):

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:45.527
that's here.
And the third equilibrium is

00:10:45.527 --> 00:10:47.570
((Down, down),
right).

00:10:50.870 --> 00:10:53.912
So there are three pure
strategy Nash equilibria in this

00:10:53.912 --> 00:10:56.149
game.
Let's just see what they do.

00:10:56.149 --> 00:11:00.331
So the first one ((Up,
up), left) is Up,

00:11:00.331 --> 00:11:05.813
left, up so it gets us to here.
So this one is the same

00:11:05.813 --> 00:11:10.040
equilibrium as corresponds to
backward induction.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:13.221
Is that right?
This one's the backward

00:11:13.221 --> 00:11:15.523
induction equilibrium,
and the other two are

00:11:15.523 --> 00:11:17.390
different.
((Down, up),

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:22.071
right) and ((Down,
down), right) both end up down

00:11:22.071 --> 00:11:25.679
here exiting the game
immediately,

00:11:25.679 --> 00:11:29.661
so both of these other
equilibria fail backward

00:11:29.661 --> 00:11:33.118
induction.
So let's put backward induction

00:11:33.118 --> 00:11:36.785
with a line through it:
they're failing backward

00:11:36.785 --> 00:11:39.730
induction.
So you might ask why are they

00:11:39.730 --> 00:11:41.946
equilibria?
We've seen examples like this

00:11:41.946 --> 00:11:43.899
before, for example,
in the entry game.

00:11:43.899 --> 00:11:45.840
We looked at some examples last
time.

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:49.180
So, in this game,
the reason these are equilibria

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:53.494
even though they fail backward
induction exactly coincides with

00:11:53.494 --> 00:11:57.600
that conversation we just had
about worrying about the other

00:11:57.600 --> 00:12:01.083
person screwing up.
So, in particular,

00:12:01.083 --> 00:12:06.991
if Player 1 thinks that Player
2 is choosing right--that is to

00:12:06.991 --> 00:12:09.201
say,
thinks that Player 2 is going

00:12:09.201 --> 00:12:12.107
to screw up--then Player 1
doesn't want to travel up the

00:12:12.107 --> 00:12:14.960
tree because she knows she'll be
carried down here,

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:19.580
and instead she just chooses
the safe option and gets 2.

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:22.695
So from Player 1's point of
view, if Player 2 was going to

00:12:22.695 --> 00:12:24.935
choose right,
then getting out of the game

00:12:24.935 --> 00:12:28.159
doing the safe thing is the best
response for Player 1.

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:31.192
And for Player 2's point of
view, if Player 1's exiting the

00:12:31.192 --> 00:12:34.277
game it really doesn't matter
what Player 2 says she's going

00:12:34.277 --> 00:12:37.115
to do,
because she doesn't get to move

00:12:37.115 --> 00:12:40.700
anyway so that's why these are
both equilibria.

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:44.663
Okay, so what we're going to do
next, we've translated this into

00:12:44.663 --> 00:12:46.291
a tree.
We've written down the

00:12:46.291 --> 00:12:48.751
strategies.
We want to actually see which

00:12:48.751 --> 00:12:51.800
of these Nash equilibria are
sub-game perfect?

00:12:55.429 --> 00:12:58.163
Let me give myself a bit more
room here because I want to keep

00:12:58.163 --> 00:13:02.494
this in sight.
So let's get rid of this and

00:13:02.494 --> 00:13:04.560
raise this one.

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:13.763
So the next question is which
of these three Nash equilibria

00:13:13.763 --> 00:13:17.840
are sub-game perfect?
To do that we need to start by

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:20.302
identifying the sub-games.
And, of course,

00:13:20.302 --> 00:13:22.475
just having hoisted that board
up there, I have to hoist it

00:13:22.475 --> 00:13:24.801
down again.
Okay, so what are the sub-games

00:13:24.801 --> 00:13:28.450
here?
Well the simplest sub-game is

00:13:28.450 --> 00:13:35.049
this simple sub-game at the end,
in which Player 1 moves.

00:13:35.049 --> 00:13:38.720
That's a very obvious sub-game,
is that right?

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.470
That's a little game within a
game, it's a rather trivial game

00:13:41.470 --> 00:13:43.769
because it's a one player game,
but it is a game.

00:13:43.769 --> 00:13:48.889
So let's examine that one
first, that's the last sub-game.

00:13:48.889 --> 00:13:54.650
So the last sub-game here is a
somewhat trivial sub-game.

00:13:54.650 --> 00:13:58.162
It looks like this.
Player 1 is the only mover and

00:13:58.162 --> 00:14:02.160
they're choosing either up or
down and the payoffs are (4,3)

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:06.293
and (3,1): and frankly we don't
really care at this point what

00:14:06.293 --> 00:14:10.155
Player 2's payoffs are because
Player 1 is the only person

00:14:10.155 --> 00:14:13.806
who's playing in this sub-game.
But nevertheless,

00:14:13.806 --> 00:14:18.629
let's put them there.
And if we write this up as a

00:14:18.629 --> 00:14:24.440
matrix--here it is as a matrix.
Since Player 1 is the only

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:28.946
mover they're choosing between
up and down, and the payoffs are

00:14:28.946 --> 00:14:32.290
(4,3) and (3,1),
and of course Player 2 doesn't

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:35.779
get to move so Player 2 is
irrelevant here.

00:14:35.779 --> 00:14:41.718
And clearly the only Nash
equilibria in this game is for

00:14:41.718 --> 00:14:45.487
Player 1 to choose up.
Player 2, it doesn't really

00:14:45.487 --> 00:14:47.711
matter what they choose,
there's nothing they can do

00:14:47.711 --> 00:14:50.570
about it anyway,
but for Player 1 to choose up

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:54.671
is the Nash equilibria.
So the Nash equilibria in this

00:14:54.671 --> 00:14:57.820
trivial sub-game is 1 just
chooses up.

00:14:57.820 --> 00:15:01.549
Is that right?
So let's look at the play

00:15:01.549 --> 00:15:06.148
induced by our three candidate
Nash equilibria in this

00:15:06.148 --> 00:15:09.765
sub-game.
So each of our candidate Nash

00:15:09.765 --> 00:15:13.940
equilibria--here they are,
this one, this one,

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:17.585
and this one--have an
instruction of how Player 1

00:15:17.585 --> 00:15:21.549
should play in this sub-game.
And let me just pause a second.

00:15:21.549 --> 00:15:25.431
The reason that these three
equilibria have an instruction

00:15:25.431 --> 00:15:29.585
for how Player 1 should play in
the sub-game is because of our

00:15:29.585 --> 00:15:34.070
definition of a strategy.
Each strategy tells the player

00:15:34.070 --> 00:15:39.259
how they should move at every
information set of that player.

00:15:39.259 --> 00:15:42.912
So even if the strategy is such
that that information set won't

00:15:42.912 --> 00:15:46.448
be reached, the strategy still
has to tell you what you would

00:15:46.448 --> 00:15:49.295
do when you got there.
And now for the first time

00:15:49.295 --> 00:15:52.179
perhaps we're going to see why
that redundancy helps us.

00:15:52.179 --> 00:15:53.830
So let's look at the
instructions.

00:15:53.830 --> 00:15:55.309
Each of them gives an
instruction.

00:15:55.309 --> 00:16:07.389
The first one tells us to play
up in this sub-game.

00:16:07.389 --> 00:16:18.570
The second one says up again,
and notice this was redundant.

00:16:18.570 --> 00:16:21.722
Once you've chosen Down you
know you're not going to get to

00:16:21.722 --> 00:16:24.606
make a choice at the third node,
or your second node,

00:16:24.606 --> 00:16:27.560
but nevertheless there's the
instruction and it says up.

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:38.290
The third one says down.
So this is the instructions of

00:16:38.290 --> 00:16:42.019
these three equilibria in this
little sub-game.

00:16:42.019 --> 00:16:47.242
This is the play prescribed by
these three equilibria in this

00:16:47.242 --> 00:16:50.398
sub-game.
Two of them say up and those

00:16:50.398 --> 00:16:54.480
ones are going to induce the
Nash equilibrium in this

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:57.620
sub-game, but the third one does
not.

00:16:57.620 --> 00:17:00.549
The third one says down and
that's not allowed.

00:17:00.549 --> 00:17:04.516
That's not allowed in a
sub-game perfect equilibrium

00:17:04.516 --> 00:17:08.716
because a sub-game perfect
equilibrium has to prescribe

00:17:08.716 --> 00:17:11.750
play in every sub-game that's
Nash,

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:15.533
and here the third equilibrium
is telling Player 1 to choose

00:17:15.533 --> 00:17:19.060
down which is not a Nash
equilibrium in the sub-game.

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:24.359
So what are we doing here?
Let's make it clear.

00:17:24.359 --> 00:17:29.569
We're finding the sub-game
perfect equilibria.

00:17:29.569 --> 00:17:43.725
And what we've done is:
number 3 is eliminated because

00:17:43.725 --> 00:18:00.819
it induces play in this sub-game
that is not Nash equilibrium,

00:18:00.819 --> 00:18:03.759
not a Nash equilibrium in the
sub-game.

00:18:03.759 --> 00:18:05.822
We're really putting stuff
together now:

00:18:05.822 --> 00:18:07.779
to be able to draw this
conclusion,

00:18:07.779 --> 00:18:12.277
we really used the fact that
strategy 3 contained a redundant

00:18:12.277 --> 00:18:16.700
instruction, an instruction down
at this node that was never

00:18:16.700 --> 00:18:18.962
reached.
But that helped us get rid of

00:18:18.962 --> 00:18:22.970
it.
So that one's gone: 3 is gone.

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:27.324
Let's proceed.
I'm going to run out of board

00:18:27.324 --> 00:18:29.960
space here.
Have people got this one down?

00:18:29.960 --> 00:18:36.620
I'll bring it back in a second,
almost, let me give it a

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:40.047
second.
What I want to do now is look

00:18:40.047 --> 00:18:43.123
at the next sub-game.
Maybe what I can do if I just

00:18:43.123 --> 00:18:45.281
remove this comment,
I can work on the right hand

00:18:45.281 --> 00:18:47.170
board, that'll allow you to look
at it.

00:18:47.170 --> 00:18:50.369
So all that comment said was 3
is eliminated.

00:18:50.369 --> 00:18:52.896
Let me work now on the right
hand half of this board,

00:18:52.896 --> 00:18:55.180
that'll allow it to be up there
a bit longer.

00:18:55.180 --> 00:18:57.989
Okay, so let's now look at the
next sub-game,

00:18:57.989 --> 00:19:00.990
and again, we're going to work
from the back.

00:19:00.990 --> 00:19:05.995
So the next sub-game back is
the sub-game that starts from

00:19:05.995 --> 00:19:10.650
this node, the sub-game that
starts from that node.

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:16.670
So let's identify that in a
different color.

00:19:16.670 --> 00:19:18.720
I used blue so let me use pink.

00:19:22.029 --> 00:19:26.908
So now we're going to look at
this sub-game,

00:19:26.908 --> 00:19:33.036
this big pink sub-game,
and again in this pink sub-game

00:19:33.036 --> 00:19:39.176
this game looks like this.
It starts with Player 2

00:19:39.176 --> 00:19:46.670
choosing between left and right,
and then Player 1 has to choose

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:53.569
up or down, and the payoffs are
(1,2), (4,3) and (3,1).

00:19:53.569 --> 00:19:56.545
Once again let's look at the
matrix form of this sub-game,

00:19:56.545 --> 00:19:59.363
and this is a little bit less
trivial than the last one

00:19:59.363 --> 00:20:02.130
because now there are really two
players playing.

00:20:02.130 --> 00:20:07.960
So here's the matrix that goes
along with this.

00:20:07.960 --> 00:20:16.164
Player 1 is choosing between up
or down and Player 2 is choosing

00:20:16.164 --> 00:20:20.434
between left or right.
And this is slightly,

00:20:20.434 --> 00:20:23.595
slightly cheating because in
fact, Player 1 of course knows

00:20:23.595 --> 00:20:26.920
what Player 2 is going to have
done by the time she moves,

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:30.539
but never mind it'll do for now.
Let's just put the payoffs in.

00:20:30.539 --> 00:20:38.610
So (up, left) is (4,3) and
(down, left) is (3,1) and (up,

00:20:38.610 --> 00:20:45.240
right) is (1,2) and this must
also be (1,2).

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:48.720
Everyone happy with that?
Just putting the payoffs in.

00:20:48.720 --> 00:20:52.202
And let's just look again at
pure-strategy Nash equilibria

00:20:52.202 --> 00:20:53.999
here.
There are actually mixed ones,

00:20:53.999 --> 00:20:56.099
but let's just worry about pure
ones for now.

00:20:56.099 --> 00:21:02.393
So the pure Nash equilibria
here in this little sub-game are

00:21:02.393 --> 00:21:03.950
what?
Well, let's just see.

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:13.190
If 2 chose left then 1 wants to
choose up.

00:21:13.190 --> 00:21:16.962
If 2 chooses right it doesn't
really matter what 1 chooses

00:21:16.962 --> 00:21:20.140
because she isn't going to get
to move anyway.

00:21:20.140 --> 00:21:26.869
Conversely, if 1 chooses up
then 2 wants to choose left.

00:21:26.869 --> 00:21:30.221
That's the example of 1 not
screwing up, so 2 wants to stay

00:21:30.221 --> 00:21:32.930
in the game.
But if 1 was to choose down

00:21:32.930 --> 00:21:36.239
then Player 2 would like to get
out of the game,

00:21:36.239 --> 00:21:40.182
so if Player 2 thinks 1 is
going to screw up she wants to

00:21:40.182 --> 00:21:43.152
exit the game.
Very quickly we can see there

00:21:43.152 --> 00:21:46.930
are two equilibria here.
One of them is (up,

00:21:46.930 --> 00:21:52.170
left) and the other one is
(down, right).

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:57.167
They correspond to playing down
this way, that's (down,

00:21:57.167 --> 00:22:01.240
right) and (up,
left) playing up this way.

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:05.656
Once again, let's look at our
three equilibria in the parent

00:22:05.656 --> 00:22:08.717
game.
Here's our three equilibria in

00:22:08.717 --> 00:22:12.439
the parent game,
and let's see what play they

00:22:12.439 --> 00:22:16.997
induced in this little sub-game.
So we'll do exactly what we did

00:22:16.997 --> 00:22:19.163
before.
So 1,2, and 3:

00:22:19.163 --> 00:22:24.549
these are our three equilibria
from above.

00:22:24.549 --> 00:22:29.984
And equilibrium number 1,
((Up, up), left) in this game

00:22:29.984 --> 00:22:32.400
prescribes (up,
left).

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:38.839
Is that right?
Equilibrium number 2,

00:22:38.839 --> 00:22:47.288
((Down, up),
right) here prescribes up,

00:22:47.288 --> 00:22:51.866
right.
And equilibrium number 3,

00:22:51.866 --> 00:22:56.299
((Down, down),
right) here prescribes (down,

00:22:56.299 --> 00:22:57.330
right).

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:04.896
So which of these are
prescribing Nash equilibria in

00:23:04.896 --> 00:23:07.048
the sub-game?
Well (up, left) is an

00:23:07.048 --> 00:23:08.380
equilibrium.
It's that one.

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:11.019
(up, left) is an equilibrium so
this is okay.

00:23:11.019 --> 00:23:14.835
And (down, right) was an
equilibrium, so 3 is okay in

00:23:14.835 --> 00:23:22.410
this sub-game.
But (up, right) is not a Nash

00:23:22.410 --> 00:23:26.925
equilibrium.
So in this sub-game,

00:23:26.925 --> 00:23:30.381
Nash equilibrium number 2,
the ((Down, up),

00:23:30.381 --> 00:23:34.577
right) equilibrium is
prescribing play that is not a

00:23:34.577 --> 00:23:39.349
Nash equilibrium in the
sub-game: so it's eliminated.

00:23:39.349 --> 00:23:42.349
It can't be a sub-game perfect
equilibrium.

00:23:42.349 --> 00:23:56.314
So here 2 is eliminated since
it induces non-Nash equilibrium

00:23:56.314 --> 00:24:01.900
play in this sub-game.

00:24:05.589 --> 00:24:08.500
Now we're done,
we know about the whole thing.

00:24:08.500 --> 00:24:11.606
So what we did here we started
with the whole game,

00:24:11.606 --> 00:24:14.339
we found there were three Nash
equilibria,

00:24:14.339 --> 00:24:17.840
we found that only one of them
agreed with backward induction.

00:24:17.840 --> 00:24:21.020
We then looked at the sub-games.
We first of all looked at that

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:23.829
blue sub-game and we found that
one of the equilibria,

00:24:23.829 --> 00:24:25.950
equilibrium number 3,
was eliminated.

00:24:25.950 --> 00:24:29.521
Equilibrium number 3 is not
prescribing Nash behavior in

00:24:29.521 --> 00:24:32.884
this sub-game.
Then we looked at the slightly

00:24:32.884 --> 00:24:36.450
more complicated sub-game,
the pink sub-game,

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:40.514
and we found that equilibrium
number 2 prescribes the behavior

00:24:40.514 --> 00:24:43.779
(up, right) which is not Nash in
this sub-game.

00:24:43.779 --> 00:24:47.218
At this stage we've eliminated
two of the three equilibria and

00:24:47.218 --> 00:24:51.116
we're just left with one.
And the one we're left with,

00:24:51.116 --> 00:24:55.021
the only sub-game perfect
equilibrium, the only

00:24:55.021 --> 00:24:59.520
equilibrium that wasn't
eliminated by the fact that it

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:03.509
would prescribe bad behavior in
sub-games,

00:25:03.509 --> 00:25:08.622
the only SPE is number 1:
which is (Up,

00:25:08.622 --> 00:25:12.670
up) and left.
What do we notice?

00:25:12.670 --> 00:25:15.775
We notice that that's the
equilibrium, that's the play

00:25:15.775 --> 00:25:18.470
that backward induction would
have selected.

00:25:18.470 --> 00:25:31.610
So notice this is the backward
induction prediction.

00:25:36.490 --> 00:25:40.697
So what are the lessons here?
The lessons here are that our

00:25:40.697 --> 00:25:44.985
new idea, the idea of sub-game
perfect equilibrium is pretty

00:25:44.985 --> 00:25:48.775
easy to go about finding.
You just look at sub-games and

00:25:48.775 --> 00:25:52.170
check that the play in each
sub-game has to be Nash play.

00:25:52.170 --> 00:25:55.434
If you start at the back,
you construct it by rolling

00:25:55.434 --> 00:25:58.509
backwards, much like we did
backward induction.

00:25:58.509 --> 00:26:01.089
Start at the last sub-game and
work backwards.

00:26:01.089 --> 00:26:03.979
The second thing is--not
surprisingly given that

00:26:03.979 --> 00:26:06.992
remark--not surprisingly,
where backward induction

00:26:06.992 --> 00:26:09.456
applies,
for example in this game,

00:26:09.456 --> 00:26:12.564
the sub-game perfect
equilibrium will find the

00:26:12.564 --> 00:26:16.569
equilibrium that is consistent
with backward induction.

00:26:16.569 --> 00:26:18.480
Remember that was our aim last
week.

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:21.895
We wanted a way of refining
Nash equilibrium to throw away

00:26:21.895 --> 00:26:25.311
those Nash equilibria that were
inconsistent with backward

00:26:25.311 --> 00:26:27.571
induction.
So sub-game perfect equilibrium

00:26:27.571 --> 00:26:29.912
has done that.
It tells us now if backward

00:26:29.912 --> 00:26:32.851
induction applies,
the Nash equilibria you should

00:26:32.851 --> 00:26:35.789
focus on are the sub-game
perfect equilibria.

00:26:35.789 --> 00:26:41.365
Indeed, most people in the
class played that equilibrium

00:26:41.365 --> 00:26:43.818
just now.
Okay so that was really what I

00:26:43.818 --> 00:26:46.272
wanted to say about this
example, but let me just make a

00:26:46.272 --> 00:26:48.162
remark in passing.
I made this remark in the

00:26:48.162 --> 00:26:49.609
middle, so let me just make it
again.

00:26:49.609 --> 00:26:54.510
When we write down strategies,
those strategies tell us what

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:58.540
seem to redundant moves.
But being forced to write down

00:26:58.540 --> 00:27:02.280
those redundant moves is useful
because it allows us to model

00:27:02.280 --> 00:27:05.834
what other people think you
would have done at those later

00:27:05.834 --> 00:27:08.274
nodes.
And sometimes I have to think

00:27:08.274 --> 00:27:11.844
what you think I would have done
at this later node before I

00:27:11.844 --> 00:27:14.809
decide not to go down that
branch of the tree.

00:27:14.809 --> 00:27:17.587
So being able to write down
everything in a strategy allows

00:27:17.587 --> 00:27:20.413
us to have everything in front
of us and makes that analysis

00:27:20.413 --> 00:27:22.306
simple;
and that's exactly what we did

00:27:22.306 --> 00:27:24.303
here.
So this was a fairly mundane

00:27:24.303 --> 00:27:27.690
example, because in particular
we didn't use any kind of

00:27:27.690 --> 00:27:30.334
information set.
So next let's look at an

00:27:30.334 --> 00:27:33.100
example that does use some
information sets.

00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:37.030
So: new example.
Let me clean this off.

00:27:47.170 --> 00:27:51.750
Once again, I want to play this
example.

00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:58.416
But what I'd really like to
do--we're going to call this

00:27:58.416 --> 00:28:05.568
game the matchmaker game--and
what I'd actually like to find

00:28:05.568 --> 00:28:12.356
out is: do we still have our
couple we tried to send on a

00:28:12.356 --> 00:28:15.508
date?
Our hapless couple we tried to

00:28:15.508 --> 00:28:17.690
send on a date at about week
three.

00:28:17.690 --> 00:28:19.253
Are you guys still here?
There's the guy,

00:28:19.253 --> 00:28:20.720
what's your name again?
Student: David.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:24.129
Professor Ben Polak:
David, and what was the--is

00:28:24.129 --> 00:28:26.660
she hiding?
There she is thank you.

00:28:26.660 --> 00:28:27.970
Your name was?
Student: Nina.

00:28:27.970 --> 00:28:30.119
Professor Ben Polak:
Nina and David.

00:28:30.119 --> 00:28:33.980
Good, can we get some mikes to
Nina and David actually?

00:28:33.980 --> 00:28:39.767
Let me do it.
I'll go on talking while I'm

00:28:39.767 --> 00:28:43.322
doing this–.
Where's David,

00:28:43.322 --> 00:28:48.370
and Ale can you get a mike to
Nina?

00:28:48.370 --> 00:28:50.944
That would be great thank you.
All right, so for weeks we've

00:28:50.944 --> 00:28:53.119
been trying to get this couple
to go on a date.

00:28:53.119 --> 00:28:57.611
It's our attempt to get
economics majors to become real

00:28:57.611 --> 00:28:59.998
people.
It's a hard thing to do and

00:28:59.998 --> 00:29:03.336
they're kind of the hapless
couple because first we sent

00:29:03.336 --> 00:29:07.220
them to the movies and they end
up going to different movies;

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:09.501
and then we sent them off for a
romantic weekend in New England

00:29:09.501 --> 00:29:11.009
and they end up doing different
things,

00:29:11.009 --> 00:29:12.961
one went to the theatre and
another one apple picking,

00:29:12.961 --> 00:29:14.250
I forget which way around it
was.

00:29:14.250 --> 00:29:17.156
And at this point,
I figure I'm a pretty bad

00:29:17.156 --> 00:29:19.859
matchmaker so what I'm going to
do is.

00:29:19.859 --> 00:29:23.271
I'm going to introduce a third
player into the game as the

00:29:23.271 --> 00:29:25.321
matchmaker.
So first of all I'll write down

00:29:25.321 --> 00:29:27.826
what the game is.
So the game at this point--the

00:29:27.826 --> 00:29:31.768
game is going to look like this.
Player 1 is the matchmaker,

00:29:31.768 --> 00:29:35.986
we can call him Player M if you
like, and he has a choice,

00:29:35.986 --> 00:29:42.246
he or she has a choice.
She could not send the couple

00:29:42.246 --> 00:29:50.920
out on a date or she could send
the couple out on a date.

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:55.132
But being a better matchmaker
than me, if she sends them out

00:29:55.132 --> 00:29:59.487
on a date, she's going to stake
some money, she'll pay for the

00:29:59.487 --> 00:30:02.164
date.
And in the date once again

00:30:02.164 --> 00:30:05.138
they're trying to meet,
and once again,

00:30:05.138 --> 00:30:08.582
unfortunately,
they haven't figured out where

00:30:08.582 --> 00:30:10.606
to meet.
We'll put the payoffs in,

00:30:10.606 --> 00:30:12.859
in a second and we'll tell you
what the strategies are.

00:30:12.859 --> 00:30:18.433
So what I'm going to assume
here is I'm going to let Jake

00:30:18.433 --> 00:30:21.319
our T.A.
be our matchmaker.

00:30:21.319 --> 00:30:24.299
And the reason I'm choosing
Jake is I think he's the nearest

00:30:24.299 --> 00:30:27.430
thing I have in mind in this
class to being a Jewish mother.

00:30:27.430 --> 00:30:30.343
I mean: he's neither Jewish--I
think he's not Jewish and he's

00:30:30.343 --> 00:30:32.375
not my mother,
but he is the T.A.,

00:30:32.375 --> 00:30:36.275
who's responsible for bringing
some drink everyday in case I

00:30:36.275 --> 00:30:38.795
pass out in the lecture.
So that's the nearest thing I

00:30:38.795 --> 00:30:40.528
can think of.
So Jake's going to be our

00:30:40.528 --> 00:30:43.010
Jewish mother,
and Jake's going to either send

00:30:43.010 --> 00:30:45.904
these guys on a date or not.
And Jake's smarter than me at

00:30:45.904 --> 00:30:47.579
this: he's actually good at
matchmaking.

00:30:47.579 --> 00:30:49.340
And what he's going to do is,
he's going to send them

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:51.439
somewhere where they really--he
