00:34:29.600 --> 00:34:33.079
So good: that worked very well.
Let's have a look now at this.

00:34:33.079 --> 00:34:36.130
Let's analyze this game and see
what we can do with this game.

00:34:36.130 --> 00:34:37.820
So how are we going to analyze
this game?

00:34:37.820 --> 00:34:40.902
So no surprise we're going to
use the idea of a sub-game

00:34:40.902 --> 00:34:43.593
perfect equilibrium,
I'll collect the mikes later

00:34:43.593 --> 00:34:46.363
don't worry.
So we're going to use the idea

00:34:46.363 --> 00:34:48.550
of a sub-game perfect
equilibrium.

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:52.050
So how do we figure out how to
work out what a sub-game perfect

00:34:52.050 --> 00:34:54.614
equilibrium is?
We're going to use the same

00:34:54.614 --> 00:34:58.062
basic idea that we used--what
we've been using all along in

00:34:58.062 --> 00:35:00.911
backward induction.
It's the same idea in the game

00:35:00.911 --> 00:35:03.877
we just looked at just now.
What we're going to do is,

00:35:03.877 --> 00:35:07.519
rather than start from the last
decision node (we can't do that

00:35:07.519 --> 00:35:10.780
anymore) and work backwards,
instead of doing that,

00:35:10.780 --> 00:35:14.118
we're going to start from the
last sub-game and work

00:35:14.118 --> 00:35:16.881
backwards.
In this example it's pretty

00:35:16.881 --> 00:35:19.360
obvious what the last sub-game
is.

00:35:19.360 --> 00:35:23.050
The last sub-game,
the game within a game--there

00:35:23.050 --> 00:35:27.605
is only really one--the game
within the game is this object

00:35:27.605 --> 00:35:30.193
here, is that right?
This is the game within the

00:35:30.193 --> 00:35:31.894
game.
Now, I could at this stage,

00:35:31.894 --> 00:35:35.313
I could do something else.
I could write down the whole

00:35:35.313 --> 00:35:39.260
matrix for the whole game and
have Jake choose the matrix,

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:42.187
and Dave and Nina choose the
row and the column,

00:35:42.187 --> 00:35:44.429
but that's going to get us
astray.

00:35:44.429 --> 00:35:46.559
So I mean we could do that but
let's not worry about that.

00:35:46.559 --> 00:35:48.639
Let's just start doing things
backwards.

00:35:48.639 --> 00:35:52.444
So when we do things backwards
we'll start at the last sub-game

00:35:52.444 --> 00:35:55.327
and that last sub-game is an old
friend of ours,

00:35:55.327 --> 00:35:58.310
it looks exactly like this.
Let's just write it in.

00:35:58.310 --> 00:36:06.138
So it involves Players 2 and 3.
And 2 was choosing between

00:36:06.138 --> 00:36:09.498
Gaddis and Spence.
And 3 was choosing between

00:36:09.498 --> 00:36:14.032
Gaddis and Spence.
And their payoffs were--let me

00:36:14.032 --> 00:36:18.795
leave a space here--so it was
(2,1), (1,2),

00:36:18.795 --> 00:36:21.814
(0,0), (0,0).
So here are the payoffs of the

00:36:21.814 --> 00:36:24.264
relevant players in the game but
while we're here why don't we

00:36:24.264 --> 00:36:28.988
put in Jake's payoffs as well.
So Jake's payoffs were 1 here,

00:36:28.988 --> 00:36:32.500
1 here, -1 here,
and -1 there.

00:36:32.500 --> 00:36:35.393
So the only relevant players
here are Players 2 and 3,

00:36:35.393 --> 00:36:38.122
but I've put Player 1's payoffs
in as well because:

00:36:38.122 --> 00:36:40.469
why not, why not just keep
track of it.

00:36:40.469 --> 00:36:44.692
Everyone happy that that
exactly describes this little

00:36:44.692 --> 00:36:46.857
game?
For all intents and purposes we

00:36:46.857 --> 00:36:49.190
can forget the first payoff but
there it is.

00:36:49.190 --> 00:36:52.030
This is a game we've seen many
times so far.

00:36:52.030 --> 00:36:55.635
It's the battle of the sexes,
or the battle of Dave and Nina,

00:36:55.635 --> 00:36:59.179
and in this game we already
know what the equilibria are.

00:36:59.179 --> 00:37:03.477
So the equilibria here,
let me just underline the best

00:37:03.477 --> 00:37:07.407
responses.
So if Nina is choosing Gaddis

00:37:07.407 --> 00:37:12.803
then Dave chooses Gaddis.
If Nina is choosing Spence then

00:37:12.803 --> 00:37:17.139
Dave would like to choose Spence
and conversely.

00:37:17.139 --> 00:37:19.136
So I've just underlined the
best responses for the players

00:37:19.136 --> 00:37:21.133
who are actually involved in the
game and haven't bothered

00:37:21.133 --> 00:37:23.129
underlining anything for Jake
because he isn't a player in

00:37:23.129 --> 00:37:24.699
this game.
Does that make sense?

00:37:24.699 --> 00:37:33.394
So the pure Nash equilibria in
this game are essentially

00:37:33.394 --> 00:37:39.560
(Gaddis, Gaddis) or (Spence,
Spence).

00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:44.431
That's pretty easy.
From Jake's point of view,

00:37:44.431 --> 00:37:50.070
each of these pure strategy
Nash equilibria yield a payoff

00:37:50.070 --> 00:37:53.219
for him of what?
What does he get?

00:37:53.219 --> 00:37:55.717
If they go to (Gaddis,
Gaddis), he's happy that they

00:37:55.717 --> 00:37:57.873
met and he gets 1 and if they
choose (Spence,

00:37:57.873 --> 00:38:00.420
Spence), he's happy that they
met and he gets 1.

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:04.181
Jake himself doesn't really
mind whether Dave and Nina learn

00:38:04.181 --> 00:38:06.860
about China or learn about the
Cold War.

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:12.280
He just wants them to meet.
So, both of these yield 1 for

00:38:12.280 --> 00:38:18.709
Jake.
They both yield a value of 1

00:38:18.709 --> 00:38:24.059
for Player 1,
who is Jake.

00:38:24.059 --> 00:38:29.239
So from Jake's point of view,
going back a stage--what we're

00:38:29.239 --> 00:38:32.030
going to do now,
just as we did with backward

00:38:32.030 --> 00:38:34.019
induction, we're going to roll
the game back.

00:38:34.019 --> 00:38:37.328
So we started by analyzing this
sub-game and now we're going to

00:38:37.328 --> 00:38:39.942
roll it back a stage,
just as we did with backward

00:38:39.942 --> 00:38:43.286
induction.
So when we roll back Jake is

00:38:43.286 --> 00:38:49.034
moving here, if Jake chooses not
to send them then we get (0,0,

00:38:49.034 --> 00:38:54.227
0) but the key part of this is
the first 0, that's Jake's

00:38:54.227 --> 00:38:58.711
payoff.
And if Jake sends them,

00:38:58.711 --> 00:39:07.068
then what Jake gets is the
value to Jake--I'll put in Jake

00:39:07.068 --> 00:39:14.692
but value to Player 1--okay
value to Jake of the Nash

00:39:14.692 --> 00:39:20.698
equilibria in this sub-game.
Not a big thing to write,

00:39:20.698 --> 00:39:23.336
but that's what Jake gets.
And the others do too:

00:39:23.336 --> 00:39:26.032
the others get that as well.
In this case,

00:39:26.032 --> 00:39:30.240
rather than writing that long
piece, this is just equal to 1.

00:39:30.240 --> 00:39:34.209
Is that right?
So if Jake sends them he knows

00:39:34.209 --> 00:39:37.606
that they're going to play a
Nash equilibrium in this

00:39:37.606 --> 00:39:39.404
sub-game,
or he believes they're going to

00:39:39.404 --> 00:39:40.780
play a Nash equilibrium in this
sub-game.

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:46.437
And either of those two Nash
equilibria in the sub-game yield

00:39:46.437 --> 00:39:49.870
a payoff to Jake of 1.
So actually,

00:39:49.870 --> 00:39:54.357
one of them is 1,
one of them yields payoffs of

00:39:54.357 --> 00:39:57.243
(1,1,2);
and the other yields payoffs of

00:39:57.243 --> 00:39:59.220
(1,2,1).
But since Jake is the only

00:39:59.220 --> 00:40:01.340
mover here, let's just focus on
Jake.

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:05.206
So from Jake's point of view
he's really choosing between 0

00:40:05.206 --> 00:40:07.739
and 1, so he's going to choose
send.

00:40:07.739 --> 00:40:14.093
So the sub-game perfect
equilibrium therefore--there are

00:40:14.093 --> 00:40:19.522
actually two of them here--one
is (send, Spence,

00:40:19.522 --> 00:40:24.489
Spence), that's what actually
happened.

00:40:24.489 --> 00:40:29.510
But there's another one which
is (send, Gaddis,

00:40:29.510 --> 00:40:35.730
Gaddis) that would also have
been a pure strategy sub-game

00:40:35.730 --> 00:40:39.434
perfect equilibrium.
So in either case,

00:40:39.434 --> 00:40:41.664
what we did,
just to remind ourselves,

00:40:41.664 --> 00:40:45.280
we first of all solved the
equilibrium down the sub-game,

00:40:45.280 --> 00:40:47.670
the equilibrium in this blue
sub-game.

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:50.720
We figured how much that
equilibrium was worth for

00:40:50.720 --> 00:40:53.210
everybody--but in particular for
Jake,

00:40:53.210 --> 00:40:56.760
but for everybody--and then we
rolled that payoff back and

00:40:56.760 --> 00:41:00.094
looked at Jake's choice.
In this particular case that

00:41:00.094 --> 00:41:02.422
game has two equilibria,
(send, Spence,

00:41:02.422 --> 00:41:04.750
Spence) and (send,
Gaddis, Gaddis).

00:41:04.750 --> 00:41:08.256
However, some of you must be
suspecting at this point that

00:41:08.256 --> 00:41:11.456
there's actually another
sub-game perfect equilibrium

00:41:11.456 --> 00:41:12.940
here.
How do we know that?

00:41:12.940 --> 00:41:14.260
Well let's just think about
this game.

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:17.760
We've been trying to send this
couple on a date all semester.

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:19.679
They haven't gone on a date all
semester.

00:41:19.679 --> 00:41:21.199
I'm embarrassing them,
but they haven't gone on a date

00:41:21.199 --> 00:41:22.536
all semester.
So there must be some

00:41:22.536 --> 00:41:24.610
possibility that they would fail
to coordinate.

00:41:24.610 --> 00:41:27.082
It would be a pretty weird
notion of equilibrium that

00:41:27.082 --> 00:41:29.745
concluded that they always
manage to coordinate and hence

00:41:29.745 --> 00:41:32.530
Jake always wants to send them.
Is that right?

00:41:32.530 --> 00:41:35.210
So let's also look at the other
equilibria here.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:52.344
Now the reason there's another
equilibrium in this

00:41:52.344 --> 00:41:54.618
sub-game--sorry,
the reason there's another

00:41:54.618 --> 00:41:57.652
equilibrium in the whole
game--the reason there's another

00:41:57.652 --> 00:42:00.955
sub-game perfect equilibrium in
the whole game is that there's

00:42:00.955 --> 00:42:03.610
another Nash equilibrium in the
sub-game.

00:42:03.610 --> 00:42:06.340
What's the other Nash
equilibrium in the sub-game?

00:42:06.340 --> 00:42:14.618
They could mix.
So it turns out that in the

00:42:14.618 --> 00:42:27.360
sub-game (here it is) there's
also a third mixed equilibrium.

00:42:32.570 --> 00:42:37.829
There is a mixed Nash
equilibrium.

00:42:37.829 --> 00:42:40.090
Now we know how to work that
out.

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:42.912
We could write down a P and a
Q, and we could look for those

00:42:42.912 --> 00:42:44.969
indifference conditions and
solve it out.

00:42:44.969 --> 00:42:46.842
But this is a sub-game,
sorry this is a game,

00:42:46.842 --> 00:42:49.353
this sub-game corresponds to a
game we've seen many times in

00:42:49.353 --> 00:42:51.051
this class so far,
and I think we probably

00:42:51.051 --> 00:42:52.210
remember what that equilibrium
is.

00:42:52.210 --> 00:42:54.003
Is that right?
I do anyway,

00:42:54.003 --> 00:42:55.690
so let's see if you remember it
as well.

00:42:55.690 --> 00:42:57.739
I'll write it down and we'll
see if you all looked alarmed.

00:42:57.739 --> 00:43:04.767
So I claim the equilibrium,
the other equilibrium has Dave

00:43:04.767 --> 00:43:11.548
playing with probability
(2/3,1/3), and has Nina playing

00:43:11.548 --> 00:43:16.952
with probability (1/3,2/3).
So this is another equilibrium

00:43:16.952 --> 00:43:18.971
in the sub-game.
People remember that this was

00:43:18.971 --> 00:43:20.480
an equilibrium in battle of the
sexes?

00:43:20.480 --> 00:43:22.710
Yeah, people are nodding at me,
yeah okay.

00:43:22.710 --> 00:43:25.882
So it isn't too unintuitive.
We all know how we'd work it

00:43:25.882 --> 00:43:27.630
out.
We could go back and put in the

00:43:27.630 --> 00:43:30.466
P and the Q, but it isn't too
unintuitive, it has Dave going

00:43:30.466 --> 00:43:33.446
more often to the lecture course
that he would prefer all other

00:43:33.446 --> 00:43:35.691
things being equal;
and it has Nina going more

00:43:35.691 --> 00:43:38.126
often to the lecture course that
she would prefer all other

00:43:38.126 --> 00:43:40.388
things being equal.
And they do so in just such a

00:43:40.388 --> 00:43:42.280
way as to make each of them
indifferent.

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:48.489
Now, this sub-game induces a
different value for Jake.

00:43:48.489 --> 00:43:51.991
So suppose Jake thinks:
"I trust Dave and Nina to play

00:43:51.991 --> 00:43:55.822
a Nash equilibrium in their
sub-game but I don't know which

00:43:55.822 --> 00:44:00.050
one it is and I think maybe
they're going to play this one."

00:44:00.050 --> 00:44:03.825
So suppose Jake thinks that
this is the equilibrium that

00:44:03.825 --> 00:44:09.061
Dave and Nina are going to play.
So now should Jake send them or

00:44:09.061 --> 00:44:11.289
not?
Well let's work it out.

00:44:11.289 --> 00:44:19.971
So now if he sends them,
if Jake sends Dave and Nina,

00:44:19.971 --> 00:44:29.320
or more anonymously if Player 1
sends Players 2 and 3,

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:34.190
then with what probability will
they meet?

00:44:40.469 --> 00:44:43.199
Well this is just a little math
exercise, let's have a look at

00:44:43.199 --> 00:44:49.237
the game again.
So Dave is playing 2/3,1/3,

00:44:49.237 --> 00:44:59.579
is that right?
Nina is playing 2/3,1/3,

00:44:59.579 --> 00:45:06.545
is that right?
So the probability of their

00:45:06.545 --> 00:45:11.475
meeting is the probability of
this box, they could meet at

00:45:11.475 --> 00:45:14.083
Gaddis,
plus the probability of this

00:45:14.083 --> 00:45:17.010
box, they could meet at Spence,
is that right?

00:45:17.010 --> 00:45:22.821
So the probability of this box
is 1/3 x 2/3 so this box has

00:45:22.821 --> 00:45:28.332
probability 2/9 and the
probability of this box is 2/3 x

00:45:28.332 --> 00:45:32.340
1/3 so this box has probability
2/9.

00:45:32.340 --> 00:45:37.768
So the probability of their
meeting is 2/9 + 2/9 that makes

00:45:37.768 --> 00:45:39.949
4/9.
Everyone okay with that?

00:45:39.949 --> 00:45:44.971
So if Jake sends Dave and Nina
and they play this mixed

00:45:44.971 --> 00:45:51.660
strategy equilibrium,
then they meet with probability

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:59.292
2/9 + 2/9,2/9 at Gaddis,
2/9 at Spence for a total of

00:45:59.292 --> 00:46:04.091
4/9,
which means they failed to meet

00:46:04.091 --> 00:46:11.026
with probability--well if
they're meeting with probability

00:46:11.026 --> 00:46:17.718
of 4/9 what must be the
probability that they're failing

00:46:17.718 --> 00:46:21.289
to meet?
5/9, thank you.

00:46:21.289 --> 00:46:26.380
So they fail to meet with
probability of 5/9.

00:46:26.380 --> 00:46:31.280
So Jake's expected payoff if he
sends them, the value for Jake

00:46:31.280 --> 00:46:40.710
of this equilibrium is what?
So the value to Jake of this

00:46:40.710 --> 00:46:49.236
Nash equilibrium,
if he sends them,

00:46:49.236 --> 00:47:00.520
is 4/9 x 1 + 5/9 x -1 for a
total of -1/9.

00:47:00.520 --> 00:47:05.797
Everyone okay with that?
So if Jake sends them they fail

00:47:05.797 --> 00:47:09.800
to meet 5/9 of the time and he
gets -1 each of those times.

00:47:09.800 --> 00:47:13.267
They succeed in meeting 4/9 of
the time, he gets +1 each of

00:47:13.267 --> 00:47:15.539
those times, so his expected
payoff,

00:47:15.539 --> 00:47:19.911
his expected value from sending
Dave and Nina on the date is

00:47:19.911 --> 00:47:22.658
-1/9.
So from Jake's point of view,

00:47:22.658 --> 00:47:26.885
what this game looks like,
if he thinks that this is the

00:47:26.885 --> 00:47:31.342
Nash equilibrium being played:
if he doesn't send he gets 0

00:47:31.342 --> 00:47:37.008
and if he does,
he gets the value of this Nash

00:47:37.008 --> 00:47:42.650
equilibrium, which in this case
is -1/9.

00:47:42.650 --> 00:47:52.597
So he's not going to send and
the SPE here is (not send,

00:47:52.597 --> 00:47:59.469
"mix," "mix") where this is the
mix.

00:47:59.469 --> 00:48:03.049
So there's a third equilibrium
here in which our matchmaker

00:48:03.049 --> 00:48:06.813
says this hapless couple is just
too hapless: they're going to

00:48:06.813 --> 00:48:09.960
play the mixed strategy
equilibrium in which case it

00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.170
isn't worth my while sending
them on the date.

00:48:13.170 --> 00:48:15.227
You guys were lucky because
Jake chose the other

00:48:15.227 --> 00:48:16.934
equilibrium.
He figured you were playing the

00:48:16.934 --> 00:48:18.557
other equilibrium,
which it turned out that you

00:48:18.557 --> 00:48:20.685
were.
So in this game there were

00:48:20.685 --> 00:48:24.447
three sub-game perfect
equilibria, one for each of the

00:48:24.447 --> 00:48:28.210
Nash equilibria in the sub-game,
as it turned out.

00:48:28.210 --> 00:48:31.961
There was one in which Jake
sent them and they coordinated

00:48:31.961 --> 00:48:35.449
on the pure strategy equilibrium
in the game (S,S).

00:48:35.449 --> 00:48:38.630
There was one in which Jake
sent them and they coordinated

00:48:38.630 --> 00:48:41.809
on the pure strategy equilibrium
in the sub-game (G,G).

00:48:41.809 --> 00:48:45.149
And there's one in which Jake
didn't send them,

00:48:45.149 --> 00:48:47.690
but had he had in fact sent
them,

00:48:47.690 --> 00:48:51.034
they would have both mixed,
and hence, for a lot of the

00:48:51.034 --> 00:48:56.170
time, failed to coordinate.
Now, what's the big lesson here?

00:48:56.170 --> 00:48:59.339
The big lesson of the first
game we saw this morning was

00:48:59.339 --> 00:49:02.163
that sub-game perfect
equilibrium implies backward

00:49:02.163 --> 00:49:04.225
induction.
The big lesson of this

00:49:04.225 --> 00:49:07.707
game--other than the fact that
we're getting closer to getting

00:49:07.707 --> 00:49:11.189
Dave and Nina on their date--the
big lesson of this game is to

00:49:11.189 --> 00:49:14.099
show that to find sub-game
perfect equilibria,

00:49:14.099 --> 00:49:18.443
all you have to do is keep your
head and solve out the Nash

00:49:18.443 --> 00:49:21.289
equilibria in each of the
sub-games,

00:49:21.289 --> 00:49:25.310
roll the payoffs back up,
and then look for behavior up

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:27.761
the tree.
Once again, you look for the

00:49:27.761 --> 00:49:31.490
Nash equilibria in each of these
sub-games, roll the payoffs back

00:49:31.490 --> 00:49:33.899
up,
and then see what the optimal

00:49:33.899 --> 00:49:38.299
moves are higher up the tree.
So we have time to do one more

00:49:38.299 --> 00:49:42.535
example, and the third example I
want to do is more of an

00:49:42.535 --> 00:49:43.670
application.

00:49:48.530 --> 00:49:52.110
So far we've seen some fairly
simple examples.

00:49:52.110 --> 00:49:53.930
Now I want to do an application.

00:50:04.860 --> 00:50:08.942
The application I want to do is
kind of a classic business

00:50:08.942 --> 00:50:12.379
school case if you like,
or a mini case involving

00:50:12.379 --> 00:50:14.170
strategic investment.

00:50:22.710 --> 00:50:25.900
The game is this,
or the setting is this.

00:50:25.900 --> 00:50:29.869
There are two firms,
we'll call them A and B.

00:50:29.869 --> 00:50:33.239
And these two firms,
initially, before we start

00:50:33.239 --> 00:50:36.974
considering what we're actually
going to talk about,

00:50:36.974 --> 00:50:40.710
initially they are playing
Cournot competition.

00:50:40.710 --> 00:50:49.199
So two firms and they're
playing Cournot competition.

00:50:49.199 --> 00:50:55.329
And we can imagine that they're
producing fertilizer.

00:50:55.329 --> 00:51:03.107
And let's be specific here,
let's assume that the prices in

00:51:03.107 --> 00:51:11.152
this market are given by the
following demand curve 2 - 1/3 x

00:51:11.152 --> 00:51:15.221
[qA + qB],
so this is the demand curve

00:51:15.221 --> 00:51:21.631
that they face.
We'll assume that costs,

00:51:21.631 --> 00:51:30.150
marginal costs,
c is equal to $1 a ton.

00:51:30.150 --> 00:51:36.501
So this is the price in dollars
per ton, and the costs are $1

00:51:36.501 --> 00:51:39.191
per ton.
In a minute what we're going to

00:51:39.191 --> 00:51:41.980
do is we're going to consider a
change in this game,

00:51:41.980 --> 00:51:45.146
but before we do that let's
just remind ourselves what the

00:51:45.146 --> 00:51:47.980
Cournot equilibrium of this game
would look like.

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:50.816
Let's do a bit of a review.
So it's been a while since

00:51:50.816 --> 00:51:52.800
we've seen Cournot,
so let's remind ourselves.

00:51:52.800 --> 00:52:01.737
So I claim that the quantity,
the Cournot quantity chosen Q*

00:52:01.737 --> 00:52:08.110
has the formula [a--c]/ 3b.
Is that right?

00:52:08.110 --> 00:52:09.909
If you go back in your notes
you'll find it.

00:52:09.909 --> 00:52:11.950
I'm not going to re-solve it
here.

00:52:11.950 --> 00:52:14.402
We've done it many times.
So [a--c]/3b trust me,

00:52:14.402 --> 00:52:18.530
is what came out of our
calculation before the mid-term.

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:20.831
What I want to do is,
I just want to make sure we can

00:52:20.831 --> 00:52:22.380
translate that into numbers
here.

00:52:22.380 --> 00:52:24.921
Sorry for having it in letters,
but let's translate it into

00:52:24.921 --> 00:52:27.709
numbers.
So in particular,

00:52:27.709 --> 00:52:32.269
this a is this 2,
is that right?

00:52:32.269 --> 00:52:44.310
This c is this 1 and this b is
this 1/3, is that right?

00:52:44.310 --> 00:52:52.081
So let's just put that down.
So in this case this is

00:52:52.081 --> 00:53:01.686
[2--1]/[3 x 1/3],
so this says that this is a

00:53:01.686 --> 00:53:06.818
million tons.
So the quantity here,

00:53:06.818 --> 00:53:10.330
the Cournot quantity is a
million tons each.

00:53:10.330 --> 00:53:13.965
So: one each.
So in this equilibrium,

00:53:13.965 --> 00:53:17.940
each of these two firms is
producing a million tons of

00:53:17.940 --> 00:53:22.239
fertilizer.
What else do we know?

00:53:22.239 --> 00:53:24.840
We know therefore what prices
must be.

00:53:24.840 --> 00:53:27.079
Let's just do that before we
even get started.

00:53:27.079 --> 00:53:31.922
So prices must be [2 - 1/3]
times the quantity that the

00:53:31.922 --> 00:53:37.034
first firm produces plus the
quantity that the second firm

00:53:37.034 --> 00:53:40.208
produces.
So that's 2 - 2/3 so that

00:53:40.208 --> 00:53:43.182
should be 4/3,
if I've got that right,

00:53:43.182 --> 00:53:51.491
or one and a third.
So prices here are $1.33 per

00:53:51.491 --> 00:53:58.900
ton.
Finally profits.

00:53:58.900 --> 00:54:01.694
So profit for each firm here,
in this equilibrium,

00:54:01.694 --> 00:54:05.059
before we even start the game,
or start the more interesting

00:54:05.059 --> 00:54:07.170
part of the game,
profit is what?

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:12.489
So they're going to get $1 and
1/3 for every ton they produce.

00:54:12.489 --> 00:54:17.572
It's going to cost them $1 to
produce each ton and they're

00:54:17.572 --> 00:54:21.139
producing one million of these
things.

00:54:21.139 --> 00:54:30.029
So their profits are 1/3,
if these are millions,

00:54:30.029 --> 00:54:38.730
their profits are 1/3 of $1
million dollars.

00:54:38.730 --> 00:54:42.449
So this is their per period
profit, in each period they're

00:54:42.449 --> 00:54:46.168
doing this, each year they're
doing this and this is their

00:54:46.168 --> 00:54:49.059
profits in each period.
So this is a simple model that

00:54:49.059 --> 00:54:50.837
we've done many times before.
This is Cournot,

00:54:50.837 --> 00:54:52.820
and now we're going to make it
more interesting.

00:54:56.110 --> 00:54:59.339
If the algebra here was a bit
quick don't worry about it,

00:54:59.339 --> 00:55:01.242
check it at home,
it's just basic,

00:55:01.242 --> 00:55:05.876
basic algebra.
So now suppose that you are the

00:55:05.876 --> 00:55:10.433
manager of Firm A.
So it's a classic business

00:55:10.433 --> 00:55:12.351
school case.
I'm looking at my

00:55:12.351 --> 00:55:14.139
business-school students in the
balcony.

00:55:14.139 --> 00:55:19.991
You're the manager of Firm A
and you have to choose whether

00:55:19.991 --> 00:55:24.329
to accept an offer to rent a new
machine.

00:55:24.329 --> 00:55:28.260
So this new machine has two
features.

00:55:33.539 --> 00:55:39.212
The first--well three
features--the first feature is

00:55:39.212 --> 00:55:42.518
it only works for A.
So this machine is being

00:55:42.518 --> 00:55:45.068
offered to you.
It wouldn't fit in to Firm B's

00:55:45.068 --> 00:55:48.300
technology, so this is only
being offered for A.

00:55:48.300 --> 00:55:55.654
The second feature of this
machine is it costs $0.7 million

00:55:55.654 --> 00:55:59.777
dollars in rental.
So each year you rent this

00:55:59.777 --> 00:56:02.770
machine, you'd have to pay $0.7
million dollars.

00:56:02.770 --> 00:56:12.704
But that's the bad news.
The good news is it will lower

00:56:12.704 --> 00:56:20.679
A's costs to $0.50 a ton.
So classic business-school

00:56:20.679 --> 00:56:22.829
situation.
You're the manager of a firm.

00:56:22.829 --> 00:56:25.534
You're involved in competition
with another firm,

00:56:25.534 --> 00:56:27.320
B.
And suddenly an opportunity

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:29.690
comes along to rent some new
technology.

00:56:29.690 --> 00:56:33.886
It's going to cost you $0.7 a
year to rent this machine,

00:56:33.886 --> 00:56:37.320
but it will lower your costs by
$.50 a ton.

00:56:37.320 --> 00:56:40.518
So this is a classic thing that
you might be asked in your

00:56:40.518 --> 00:56:42.820
interview for Morgan Stanley
next week.

00:56:42.820 --> 00:56:44.537
How many of you are
