01:10:35.521 --> 01:10:38.540
its strategy,
Firm B decreases its strategy

01:10:38.540 --> 01:10:41.381
in response?
Strategic substitutes,

01:10:41.381 --> 01:10:44.035
right.
So because this is a game of

01:10:44.035 --> 01:10:47.403
strategic substitutes--good
interview word,

01:10:47.403 --> 01:10:51.733
good word to mention in an
interview--because this is a

01:10:51.733 --> 01:10:57.103
game of strategic substitutes,
we know that Firm B reduces its

01:10:57.103 --> 01:11:00.349
quantity.
As Firm B reduces its quantity

01:11:00.349 --> 01:11:05.220
is that good for A or bad for A?
It's good for A, right?

01:11:05.220 --> 01:11:17.529
This is good for Firm A,
it softens competition.

01:11:17.529 --> 01:11:21.606
As a consequence,
it leads to an increase in

01:11:21.606 --> 01:11:24.223
profit.
Again--we don't have time

01:11:24.223 --> 01:11:28.386
today--but what we could do is
we could go back and we could

01:11:28.386 --> 01:11:31.420
recalculate the new Cournot
equilibrium.

01:11:31.420 --> 01:11:38.111
We could calculate this--we
could as a homework exercise try

01:11:38.111 --> 01:11:44.690
it--calculate the new Nash
equilibrium and notice this is a

01:11:44.690 --> 01:11:51.529
Nash equilibrium in a sub-game.
Why is this a sub-game?

01:11:51.529 --> 01:11:55.779
Because Firm A made its
decision whether to buy this new

01:11:55.779 --> 01:11:59.409
machine or not,
and then they played Cournot.

01:11:59.409 --> 01:12:01.743
So the Cournot game,
the game up here,

01:12:01.743 --> 01:12:07.000
what is this?
This is the sub-game.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:09.140
This is the diagram of the
sub-game, if you like.

01:12:09.140 --> 01:12:12.180
It's the best responses of the
sub-game.

01:12:18.470 --> 01:12:21.997
So what sub-game perfection
tells us to do here is first of

01:12:21.997 --> 01:12:25.159
all, work out the new
equilibrium in the sub-game,

01:12:25.159 --> 01:12:29.540
work out how much that new
equilibrium is worth for Firm A

01:12:29.540 --> 01:12:33.460
and then roll it back to the
investment decision.

01:12:33.460 --> 01:12:46.229
It turns out when we do that we
get an extra $.31 million.

01:12:46.229 --> 01:12:51.090
So we could do it at home,
we get an extra $.31 million.

01:12:51.090 --> 01:12:53.962
So it turns out that our MBA
student was right,

01:12:53.962 --> 01:12:58.250
good.
It turns out that if you add

01:12:58.250 --> 01:13:04.162
this .31 to the .69 we had
already we get 1,

01:13:04.162 --> 01:13:12.274
which of course is much bigger
than .7 and indeed you should

01:13:12.274 --> 01:13:17.070
rent the machine.
Now, I want you to have two

01:13:17.070 --> 01:13:19.300
take away lessons from this
game.

01:13:19.300 --> 01:13:21.939
The first take away lesson is
this.

01:13:21.939 --> 01:13:25.282
When you're analyzing a game
like this, be it in the real

01:13:25.282 --> 01:13:28.743
world or in a job interview,
the first thing you want to do

01:13:28.743 --> 01:13:30.630
is what?
You want to look at the

01:13:30.630 --> 01:13:33.566
sub-game.
You want to look at what would

01:13:33.566 --> 01:13:37.611
happen if you did invest and
solve out the new Nash

01:13:37.611 --> 01:13:42.504
equilibrium in that sub-game.
Then you want to roll back the

01:13:42.504 --> 01:13:47.191
value of that sub-game back into
the initial decision which is

01:13:47.191 --> 01:13:51.263
the strategic investment
decision whether to rent this

01:13:51.263 --> 01:13:55.587
machine or not.
So schematically,

01:13:55.587 --> 01:14:02.474
the game looks like this:
rent or not rent,

01:14:02.474 --> 01:14:08.870
and in either case you play
Cournot.

01:14:08.870 --> 01:14:13.176
There's a sub-game in each case.
In this case you play symmetric

01:14:13.176 --> 01:14:16.890
Cournot, when you both have the
same costs;

01:14:16.890 --> 01:14:22.485
and here you play asymmetric
Cournot, where you have

01:14:22.485 --> 01:14:25.841
different costs.
And the way we analyze this

01:14:25.841 --> 01:14:28.041
game is, we solve out the
symmetric Cournot,

01:14:28.041 --> 01:14:31.341
we actually did that up front.
We now solve out the new

01:14:31.341 --> 01:14:34.228
equilibrium in this asymmetric
Cournot game,

01:14:34.228 --> 01:14:38.470
this one here.
This is the old one and this is

01:14:38.470 --> 01:14:40.770
the new one.
Solve it out.

01:14:40.770 --> 01:14:42.890
Work out how much profit you're
going to get.

01:14:42.890 --> 01:14:47.536
And roll that back remembering
that it costs you $.7 million to

01:14:47.536 --> 01:14:50.338
make this step.
So that's the first take away

01:14:50.338 --> 01:14:52.328
lesson.
But the second take away lesson

01:14:52.328 --> 01:14:54.504
is more general,
so let me just pause to get

01:14:54.504 --> 01:14:56.630
everyone to wake up again so I
make it.

01:14:56.630 --> 01:15:01.090
The second take away lesson is
this., What tips the balance

01:15:01.090 --> 01:15:05.396
here from the Economics answer
and the accounting answer,

01:15:05.396 --> 01:15:10.470
were the strategic effects.
It was the strategic effect.

01:15:10.470 --> 01:15:13.060
This is a strategic effect.

01:15:19.789 --> 01:15:24.932
It was the effect of the other
firm or other players changing

01:15:24.932 --> 01:15:28.509
their behavior.
And the most common mistake to

01:15:28.509 --> 01:15:32.819
make when you're thinking about
strategic decisions is what?

01:15:32.819 --> 01:15:34.800
It's to forget that they're
strategic.

01:15:34.800 --> 01:15:38.505
It's to forget that the other
players are going to change

01:15:38.505 --> 01:15:40.750
their behavior.
In this example,

01:15:40.750 --> 01:15:44.739
the other firm cuts back its
production so much as to make

01:15:44.739 --> 01:15:48.423
that investment profitable.
But let me give you two other

01:15:48.423 --> 01:15:50.529
examples.
Example number one.

01:15:50.529 --> 01:15:53.689
You're designing a tax policy
for the U.S..

01:15:53.689 --> 01:15:58.598
The dumb way to analyze this is
to say look at what people are

01:15:58.598 --> 01:16:02.300
doing now, push through the new
tax numbers,

01:16:02.300 --> 01:16:05.491
and act like an accountant and
crunch out how much money the

01:16:05.491 --> 01:16:08.760
government's going to make.
Why is that wrong?

01:16:08.760 --> 01:16:12.653
Because you're forgetting that
as you change the tax code

01:16:12.653 --> 01:16:16.199
people's behavior changes.
Incentives change and people's

01:16:16.199 --> 01:16:18.420
behavior changes.
It leads to a mistake in

01:16:18.420 --> 01:16:21.465
designing the tax code.
You need to take into account

01:16:21.465 --> 01:16:23.989
strategic effects:
how behavior changes.

01:16:23.989 --> 01:16:27.010
Example number two,
closer to home.

01:16:27.010 --> 01:16:29.369
You're designing a new
curriculum for Yale.

01:16:29.369 --> 01:16:33.033
So you change the rules of the
curriculum and when analyzing it

01:16:33.033 --> 01:16:36.578
you say--I wouldn't say this but
some people on the committee

01:16:36.578 --> 01:16:39.060
might say this--under these new
rules,

01:16:39.060 --> 01:16:42.217
if we look at what people used
to do, they will now do more of

01:16:42.217 --> 01:16:44.698
this and less of that,
and they'll learn this and

01:16:44.698 --> 01:16:46.439
learn that.
What are you missing?

01:16:46.439 --> 01:16:50.304
You're missing that students
are players and students change

01:16:50.304 --> 01:16:53.710
their behavior as you change the
curriculum rules.

01:16:53.710 --> 01:16:57.220
So the biggest lesson of
today's class is don't be like

01:16:57.220 --> 01:17:00.079
an accountant,
partly because it's boring and

01:17:00.079 --> 01:17:03.684
you won't go on your date,
and partly because you'll miss

01:17:03.684 --> 01:17:06.000
out on these important strategic
effects.

